:"Woodford, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Lady","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>lavedi</i>, <i>levedi</i>, <i>ladi</i> ‘lady, female head of a household, woman, wife’ (Old English <i>hlǣfdige</i>). As a man's name it may have been used in mockery, or be short for occupational names such as <b>Ladyman</b>.","Polish: variant of   Lada  .","Hungarian (<b>Ládi</b>): habitational name for someone from Lád in Borsod County or Lad in Somogy County."],"variants":[{"name":"Lada","meanings":["Of uncertain origin. If not simply an invention, it may have been devised as a feminine equivalent of   Alan   (of which it is an anagram), or a shortened form of   Alana .  It seems to have been first used by the American film actress  Lana Turner  (  1920–1995 ), whose original name was  Julia ."]}]},{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":32,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Matilda Kevelioc was born on 2 February 1422, in Woodford, Northamptonshire, England as the daughter of William Kevelioc. She married LORD Richard VI 'The Middle' FitzRichard Walkern on 9 April 1449, in Woodford, Northamptonshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Woodford, Northamptonshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"2 February 1422–":"2. veebruar 1422–Surnud","1422–Female":"1422–Surnud","1420–1472":"1420–1472","1418–1473":"1418–1473","1450–1559":"1450–1559","1457–1502":"1457–1502","1439–1486":"1439–1486","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","2 February 1422":"2. veebruar 1422","1473":"1473","1450":"1450","1472":"1472","1 May 1450":"1. mai 1450","1502":"1502","1457":"1457","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1422":"1422","1486":"1486","1420":"1420","9 April 1449":"9. aprill 1449","1418":"1418","1439":"1439","1559":"1559","Walkern, Hertfordshire, England":"Walkern, Hertfordshire, England","Woodford, Northampton, England":"Woodford, Northamptonshire, England","Woodford, Northamptonshire, England":"W